sentences: Justin Tokimitsu Nozuka (born September 29, 1988) is a American singer, songwriter and actor.
He then went on to the Etobicoke School of the Arts, where he graduated from in 2007.
In 2007, Nozuka released his debut album Holly.
In February 2008, Justin was nominated for a Juno award in the category of "New Artist of the Year", following the commercial and critical success of his debut album.

Nozuka's song "After Tonight" has also been featured in a commercial for Scott Baio Is 46...and Pregnant on VH1, as well as on mtvU's The Freshman.
In 2008, Nozuka toured with Marié Digby and Eric Hutchinson.

In the beginning of 2009, he toured the United States again, this time co-headlining with Missy Higgins and with special guest, Lenka.
In the summer of 2009, Nozuka began working on his second studio album, while touring and playing live shows in Europe.

The album was released in the US on April 13, 2010 and debuted at Number 118 on the Billboard 200 Albums Chart.
On February 18, 2010, Nozuka lent his vocals alongside 50 of Canada's best and brightest artists on a reworked version of K'naan's "Wavin' Flag."
It was released on iTunes Friday March 12, 2010 for purchase with all proceeds going to designated charities: World Vision, Free the Children and War Child.
Nozuka collaborated with the musical group The Slakadeliqs on their single "Love Controls the Sun" in November 2011.
Nozuka collaborated with the musical group The Slakadeliqs on their single "Love Controls the Sun" in November 2011.
The song is part of the group's debut album The Other Side of Tomorrow.
RZA, joined by Kobra Khan, James Black and Justin, released the song, also titled "Gone," in October 2011 as a tribute to former Wu-Tang Clan member the late Ol' Dirty Bastard.
In April 2014, Nozuka released his third studio album, Ulysees.
After spending 2010 touring, Nozuka took a break and started self-producing the album himself, resulting in a four-year gap between albums.
